    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-02-24T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-02-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="580"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d580">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.51G/2–2454</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Counselor</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MD1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacArthur</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Assistant Secretary of State for
                        Congressional Relations</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MTB1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morton</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-02-24">February 24,
                            1954</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>When the Secretary met with the Senate Foreign Relations Committee today to
                    report on the Berlin Conference,<note n="1" xml:id="d580fn1">For the testimony
                        of the Secretary of State regarding the Berlin Conference, Feb. 24, 1954,
                        see <hi rend="italic">Executive Sessions of the Senate Foreign Relations
                            Committee</hi>, vol. VI, pp. 153–184. For additional information on
                        reports to Congress by Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                            >Dulles</persName> on the Conference, see <ref target="frus1952-54v07p1"
                            >volume <hi rend="smallcaps">vii</hi>
                        </ref>.</note> both Senator Gillette and Senator
                        <persName>Humphrey</persName>
                    <note n="2" xml:id="d580fn2">Senators <persName>Hubert H. Humphrey</persName> of
                        Minnesota and <persName>Guy M. Gillette</persName> of Iowa.</note> were
                    extremely critical regarding our Indochina policy. Senator Gillette
                    characterized it as illogical and unsound. Senator <persName corresp="#p_HGM1"
                        >Humphrey</persName> said we had no plans for Indochina and that the
                    testimony given by Admiral <persName corresp="#p_PAAW1">Radford</persName>,
                    General <persName corresp="#p_SGWB1">Smith</persName> and Secretary <persName
                        corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName> was in his opinion conflicting and
                    inconsistent.</p>
                <p>I pass the foregoing information along simply as a matter of record so that the
                    people in <gloss target="#t_EUR1">EUR</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_FE1"
                        >FE</gloss> will know the kind of noise the two Senators are making with
                    respect to Indochina. I should add <pb facs="1107" n="1075" xml:id="pg_1075"/>
                    that one or two other voices chimed in, particularly <persName corresp="#p_MMJ1"
                        >Mike Mansfield</persName>, to the effect that our policy with respect to
                    Indochina was thus far sound and that there are a great many imponderables in
                    Indochina, Paris, etc., which probably made it very difficult to forecast the
                    future with exactitude.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MD1">Douglas MacArthur II</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
